Headline: Ashoka Pillar
Text: The Ashoka Pillar is a series of columns dispersed throughout the Indian subcontinent, erected by Emperor Ashoka during his reign in the 3rd century BCE. The most famous is at Sarnath, featuring the Lion Capital, now India's national emblem.

Headline: Dancing Girl of Mohenjo-daro
Text: A bronze statuette from the Indus Valley Civilization, dating to around 2500 BCE. It is one of the earliest known works of art from the Indian subcontinent, showcasing advanced metalworking skills.

Headline: Ajanta Cave Paintings
Text: The Ajanta Caves are renowned for their ancient Buddhist murals and sculptures, created between the 2nd century BCE and 6th century CE. These paintings depict Jataka tales and are masterpieces of Indian religious art.

Headline: Brihadeeswarar Temple
Text: Built in the 11th century CE by Raja Raja Chola I in Thanjavur, Tamil Nadu, this temple is a UNESCO World Heritage Site and a prime example of Dravidian architecture.

Headline: Taj Mahal
Text: Commissioned in 1632 by Mughal emperor Shah Jahan, the Taj Mahal is an iconic symbol of love and a masterpiece of Mughal architecture, combining elements from Islamic, Persian, and Indian styles.

Headline: Jamini Roy Painting
Text: Jamini Roy was a pioneering modern Indian artist known for his unique style inspired by Bengali folk art. His works contributed to the development of modern Indian painting in the 20th century.
